segments.text: This was May of 1960.
Don had been offered a fellowship for a graduate program.
They wanted him to stay on for a graduate program.
But since I was six months pregnant and had to terminate, he didn't have summer employment.
we knew we didn't have, we couldn't financially make it through the summer, so he decided to accept his job offer with ARCO and for us to leave.
How well, as you all began to get into the realities, how well prepared did you think A&M had made the two of you for real life?
For the real life?
I can only speak for the oil company situation because
At that time, you had a year's training under them.
And you went through all the different phases.
You went through chemical engineering.
You went through production.
You went through refinery.
And so you knew that the whole first year you would be two or three months in one location, and then you'd be moved to the next phase.
And then you would take a permanent assignment, production and drilling and so forth.
As it turned out, as Donald went through that, our first assignment was in Longview.
Then we went to Magnolia, Arkansas.
And then we went to Midland, Texas.
And then we went, I think, to Denver City, Texas.

But I can remember that when it was all over the first year, Don realized that his real love was in the drilling, and he went into the drilling end of the petroleum engineering and liked it very much and stayed with it for a number of years.
And sometime during the mid-60s, he was made an offer with Oracle Pipeline, and he went with the pipeline rather than the refining.
All right, but did you feel that A&M had prepared him well?
Technically, yes.

And they didn't spend a lot of time on how to build a life other than just... All right, as you think back on those years when you all were students, if everybody from those years could be brought here right now,
which ones would you most want to thank, give appreciation to?
You mean the ones that I worked with?
Anybody.
Oh, well, of course, I'd certainly be very grateful to Mr. Benson.
I truly loved him.
And Mr. Horsley and his son still lives here today, and we talk about those things every once in a while.
And I still see Mr. Hensel.
I appreciated him.
And Mr. McGuire, he just died last year, and I had stayed in touch with him throughout the years.
Even after I left here, every year at Christmas time, Mr. Benson would send me a handwritten Christmas card.
I was always amazed that he remembered a student wife because so many went through the office.
But after my husband died, Mr. Benson was responsible for bringing me back here.
And I shall always be grateful for that.
So there were a lot of people who taught.
And Dr. Winerdi, who's today president of Texas Medical Center, I really liked to work with Dr. Winerdi.
He made it a challenge, and he made you stretch.
And if you do that, you have to grow.
There's no way you can do otherwise.
And then, of course, I knew who John Calhoun was at that time, and I knew some of his work, and we did a little bit for him in our offices.
And I admired these people greatly, and I still do today.
I'm getting near the end of questions I can think of.
What have we not covered from those student years?
Well, the only other thing I was going to add is for a little additional income, I typed student papers for the students.
And of course, I typed all of Don's papers.
On what did you type them?
A manual typewriter.
And I didn't, an Olympic typewriter to be exact, a manual Olympic, had half space to it so you could type formulas.
With the engineers you had to have half space so you could do the formulas.
So I would type papers for my husband and Robert Lacey and any of the others that asked me to do so.
What was the, if you did it for a fee, what was the fee?
I think it was $25 a page, I mean 25 cents a page.
Did you do theses and dissertations, Amber?
No, just the class assignments.
Okay, terrible.
I reckon how often you did?
Well, every week I had a paper to do for someone, and then I think he charged five cents a copy because we had to do carbon copies.
There was no duplication other than that.
I can remember typing a paper for Don one night, and he said, well, this just goes in the stack with the rest.
We've been trashing a lot of them, and so I wadded it up and threw it in the trash.
He said, no, I meant that's a perfect one.
Keep it, and I ironed it.
I spent probably an hour on it, so I can remember taking it out and ironing it.
Do you remember any crises where you kept making an error and it wasn't easy to correct the errors then with all those carbon pages?
Oh, yes, on those formulas, yes, you had a lot of those crises.
I can remember the night before my daughter was born, Don had a major test, and it was on Saturday.

We had Saturday classes at that time, and he had a geology test, and he had a lot of words he had to know, and he was asking me to call him out to him, and I remember dodecahedron to this day, that he had to tell me what it meant and had to be able to spell it, and we were still calling out
words along about midnight and we finally decided to go to bed and she was born the next day.
My water broke sometime during the night and to this day I still remember calling out those words.
And he had to leave me at the hospital and come back to campus and take that major test because there was, you didn't dare miss a major test.
Then he returned to the hospital.
I think he made a nail on it.
It was a different era.
Now, when did you acquire that typewriter?
Do you remember?
We purchased it after we came here, yes.
What did it cost?
Oh, it might have cost $100.
That was a lot of money at that time.
Was it a new one?
Yes, brand new.
And you didn't have any crises of it breaking or anything?
No, the only crises that we really ever had on equipment was...
He did all of his formulas, of course, with slide rule.
And we had a little table in our bedroom where he studied, and we had a little lamp over it, and he laid his slide rule down.
And I left the light on at one time, and it warped just a little bit, and he had a major test the next day.
So that was kind of a crisis.
We didn't have any pocket computers.
You did slide rule.
I still have his slide rule today.
Of course, a lot of people don't know what they are.
Yes, yes.
What else have we not touched on that you can think of?
That's probably more than most people want to know.
I will say that I never thought about coming back when I left here in 1960.
I never thought about returning to Texas A&M, that that would be a major part of my life again.
But I'm so thankful that not
Glad for the reasons I came back, but that I have returned to A&M, and it's been a wonderful journey.
Well, those of us that have had the honor to work with you are glad that that pleasure was ours.
Then I have two questions left.
One is, let's make believe that someone walked up to you and gave you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M
and you decide what use they will make of the money.
If you could make a million dollar gift to Texas A&M, for what cause would you have them spend the money?
Oh, I would probably have to put it in scholarships.
For whom?
Just any student, and I wouldn't specify.
I'd say needy students, because I think there's still a need today for students who do not have the money
First-time graduates, first-time members out of a family who've ever been to college, they just don't realize what a benefit it really is for them.
Don and I were first-time college students from our families with no financial support from either side.
There were times we weren't sure we would make it financially, and if I had a gift, that's probably where I would have to leave it today.
Okay, then the last question.
What feelings do you hold in your heart for Texas A&M today?
Oh, very high ones.

I had planned to leave here when I got my children through college with their bachelor's degree and moved myself back to Dallas, and I realized I had put down roots and loved it very much, and A&M had been good to me, and this was home.
And I'll retire from Texas A&M.
